          <h2>About Geometry Dash</h2>
          
          <h3>Geometry Dash gameplay</h3>
          <p>Geometry Dash is a fast-paced platform game where you control a small cube that moves automatically from left to right. Your only job is to tap or click at the right moment to jump over spikes, gaps, and dangerous obstacles. There is no way to slow down or stop, so timing is everything.</p>
          
          <p>Each level is synchronized with an energetic soundtrack. Obstacles always appear in the same place, so repetition is part of the design. The more you play a level, the more you memorize the patterns. This mix of rhythm and memory makes Geometry Dash easy to understand but hard to master.</p>
          
          <p>As you progress, new mechanics appear: portals that change gravity, speed boosters, jump pads, and platforms that move or disappear. Sometimes the cube transforms into a ship, a ball, a UFO, or a wave, and each form has its own physics and controls.</p>
          
          <p>There is no "life bar" or health system. If you hit an obstacle, the run ends instantly and you restart from the beginning or from a checkpoint in practice mode. This "try, fail, learn, try again" loop is the core of Geometry Dash.</p>
          
          <h3>History of Geometry Dash</h3>
          <p>Geometry Dash was created by developer Robert Topala and released in 2013 for mobile devices. What started as a small one-button game quickly grew into a global success thanks to its intense gameplay and strong community of players and creators.</p>
          
          <p>Over time, new levels, icons, and game modes were added through updates. The game also introduced a powerful level editor that allowed the community to design and share their own challenges. Many of these player-made levels became as famous as the official ones.</p>
          
          <p>The success of Geometry Dash also inspired spin-off versions like <strong><a href="/geometry-dash-lite/">Geometry Dash Lite</a></strong>, <strong><a href="/geometry-dash-meltdown/">Geometry Dash Meltdown</a></strong>, <strong><a href="/geometry-dash-subzero/">Geometry Dash SubZero</a></strong>, and <strong><a href="/geometry-dash-breeze/">Geometry Dash Breeze</a></strong>. Each one adds new music, levels, and visual themes to the main formula.</p>
          
          <h3>Platforms</h3>
          <p>You can enjoy Geometry Dash on several platforms. It is available on mobile devices (iOS and Android) and also on PC through different services. On geometrydash.ie you can play a browser version that runs with HTML5, so you only need a modern web browser.</p>
          
          <p>Because the game works in the browser, you can play on Windows, macOS, Linux, and even on Chromebooks without installing anything. Just open the site, wait a few seconds for the game to load, and start jumping.</p>
          
          <hr/>
          
          <h2>How to play Geometry Dash</h2>
          
          <h3>Step-by-step instructions</h3>
          <p>1. Open <strong>geometrydash.ie</strong> in your browser and wait for the game to load completely. Make sure your sound is on to follow the music and rhythm.</p>
          
          <p>2. From the main menu, choose a level. Beginners should start with the first level to learn the basic jumps and obstacles before trying something harder.</p>
          
          <p>3. Once the level starts, your cube moves automatically. Tap, click, or press the jump key to avoid spikes and holes. Focus on the beat and watch how the level reacts to the music.</p>
          
          <p>4. When you crash, the run restarts. Try to remember where you failed and prepare your jump a bit earlier next time. Each failure teaches you something new about the level.</p>
          
          <p>5. Use practice mode when a level feels too difficult. In practice mode you can place checkpoints, so you do not need to restart from the very beginning after every mistake.</p>
          
          <h3>Controls</h3>
          <p>On PC, the default control is very simple: press the <strong>spacebar</strong>, click the <strong>left mouse button</strong>, or use the <strong>up arrow</strong> to jump. You only need one of these inputs; choose the one that feels most comfortable for you.</p>
          
          <p>On mobile, tap anywhere on the screen to jump. The timing is the same, but your finger replaces the keyboard or mouse. Because the game is so responsive, even a tiny delay in your tap can be the difference between a clean jump and a crash.</p>
          
          <h3>Basic rules</h3>
          <p>The rules of Geometry Dash are very clear:</p>
          <ul>
            <li>Your cube never stops moving forward.</li>
            <li>One mistake means instant death and restart.</li>
            <li>You win the level when you reach 100% progress.</li>
            <li>Practice mode lets you learn tough sections with checkpoints.</li>
          </ul>
          
          <p>There is no time limit, no lives counter, and no traditional "game over". You can try a level as many times as you want until you finally complete it.</p>
          
          <hr/>
          
          <h2>Tips and tricks for Geometry Dash</h2>
          <p>Success in Geometry Dash is not only about fast reaction time. It also depends on patience, rhythm, and smart practice. Listen carefully to the music, watch the level patterns, and learn where each jump should happen.</p>
          
          <ul>
            <li>Do not spam jumps. Every tap should be intentional.</li>
            <li>Use headphones to hear the beat more clearly.</li>
            <li>Start with easier levels before trying the hardest ones.</li>
            <li>Use practice mode to study sections that always kill you.</li>
            <li>Take short breaks if you feel frustrated; your focus will be better after a rest.</li>
          </ul>
          
          <hr/>
          
          <h2>Geometry Dash features</h2>
          <p>Geometry Dash combines simple controls with deep challenge and a lot of replay value. Many players keep coming back just to improve their consistency or to unlock new icons and colors.</p>
          
          <h3>Other features</h3>
